README.md
     1‚Üí# python-dotenv
     3‚Üí[![Build Status][build_status_badge]][build_status_link]
     4‚Üí[![PyPI version][pypi_badge]][pypi_link]
     5‚Üí
     6‚Üípython-dotenv reads key-value pairs from a `.env` file and can set them as
     7‚Üíenvironment variables. It helps in the development of applications following the
     8‚Üí[12-factor](https://12factor.net/) principles.
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí- [Getting Started](#getting-started)
    11‚Üí- [Other Use Cases](#other-use-cases)
    12‚Üí  - [Load configuration without altering the environment](#load-configuration-without-altering-the-environment)
    13‚Üí  - [Parse configuration as a stream](#parse-configuration-as-a-stream)
    14‚Üí  - [Load .env files in IPython](#load-env-files-in-ipython)
    15‚Üí- [Command-line Interface](#command-line-interface)
    16‚Üí- [File format](#file-format)
    17‚Üí  - [Multiline values](#multiline-values)
    18‚Üí  - [Variable expansion](#variable-expansion)
    19‚Üí- [Related Projects](#related-projects)
    20‚Üí- [Acknowledgements](#acknowledgements)
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí## Getting Started
    24‚Üí```shell
    25‚Üípip install python-dotenv
    26‚Üí```
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíIf your application takes its configuration from environment variables, like a
    29‚Üí12-factor application, launching it in development is not very practical because
    30‚Üíyou have to set those environment variables yourself.
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíTo help you with that, you can add python-dotenv to your application to make it
    33‚Üíload the configuration from a `.env` file when it is present (e.g. in
    34‚Üídevelopment) while remaining configurable via the environment:
    35‚Üí
    36‚Üí```python
    37‚Üífrom dotenv import load_dotenv
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üíload_dotenv()  # reads variables from a .env file and sets them in os.environ
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí# Code of your application, which uses environment variables (e.g. from `os.environ` or
    42‚Üí# `os.getenv`) as if they came from the actual environment.
    43‚Üí```
    44‚Üí
    45‚ÜíBy default, `load_dotenv()` will:
    46‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    78‚Üí## Other Use Cases
    80‚Üí### Load configuration without altering the environment
    82‚ÜíThe function `dotenv_values` works more or less the same way as `load_dotenv`,
    83‚Üíexcept it doesn't touch the environment, it just returns a `dict` with the
    84‚Üívalues parsed from the `.env` file.
    85‚Üí
    86‚Üí```python
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   105‚Üí### Parse configuration as a stream
   107‚Üí`load_dotenv` and `dotenv_values` accept [streams][python_streams] via their
   108‚Üí`stream` argument. It is thus possible to load the variables from sources other
   109‚Üíthan the filesystem (e.g. the network).
   110‚Üí
   111‚Üí```python
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   120‚Üí### Load .env files in IPython
   122‚ÜíYou can use dotenv in IPython. By default, it will use `find_dotenv` to search for a
   123‚Üí`.env` file:
   124‚Üí
   125‚Üí```python
   126‚Üí%load_ext dotenv
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   141‚Üí### Disable load_dotenv
   143‚ÜíSet `PYTHON_DOTENV_DISABLED=1` to disable `load_dotenv()` from loading .env
   144‚Üífiles or streams. Useful when you can't modify third-party package calls or in
   145‚Üíproduction.
   146‚Üí
   147‚Üí## Command-line Interface
   149‚ÜíA CLI interface `dotenv` is also included, which helps you manipulate the `.env`
   150‚Üífile without manually opening it.
   151‚Üí
   152‚Üí```shell
   153‚Üí$ pip install "python-dotenv[cli]"
   154‚Üí$ dotenv set USER foo
   155‚Üí$ dotenv set EMAIL foo@example.org
   156‚Üí$ dotenv list
   157‚ÜíUSER=foo
   158‚ÜíEMAIL=foo@example.org
   159‚Üí$ dotenv list --format=json
   160‚Üí{
   161‚Üí  "USER": "foo",
   162‚Üí  "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"
   163‚Üí}
   164‚Üí$ dotenv run -- python foo.py
   165‚Üí```
   166‚Üí
   167‚ÜíRun `dotenv --help` for more information about the options and subcommands.
   168‚Üí
   169‚Üí## File format
   171‚ÜíThe format is not formally specified and still improves over time. That being
   172‚Üísaid, `.env` files should mostly look like Bash files. Reading from FIFOs (named
   173‚Üípipes) on Unix systems is also supported.
   174‚Üí
   175‚ÜíKeys can be unquoted or single-quoted. Values can be unquoted, single- or
   176‚Üídouble-quoted. Spaces before and after keys, equal signs, and values are
   177‚Üíignored. Values can be followed by a comment. Lines can start with the `export`
   178‚Üídirective, which does not affect their interpretation.
   179‚Üí
   180‚ÜíAllowed escape sequences:
   181‚Üí
   182‚Üí- in single-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`
   183‚Üí- in double-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`, `\"`, `\a`, `\b`, `\f`, `\n`, `\r`, `\t`, `\v`
   184‚Üí
   185‚Üí### Multiline values
   187‚ÜíIt is possible for single- or double-quoted values to span multiple lines. The
   188‚Üífollowing examples are equivalent:
   189‚Üí
   190‚Üí```bash
   191‚ÜíFOO="first line
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   199‚Üí### Variable without a value
   201‚ÜíA variable can have no value:
   202‚Üí
   203‚Üí```bash
   204‚ÜíFOO
   205‚Üí```
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   214‚Üí### Variable expansion
   216‚Üípython-dotenv can interpolate variables using POSIX variable expansion.
   217‚Üí
   218‚ÜíWith `load_dotenv(override=True)` or `dotenv_values()`, the value of a variable
   219‚Üíis the first of the values defined in the following list:
   220‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
